---

<ToolLayout
  title="Metronome - Online Beat Keeper for Musicians | Webutilbox"
  description="Free online metronome. Adjustable BPM, time signatures, and visual beat indicator. Perfect for musicians and music practice."
  canonical={canonical}
  ogImage="https://webutilbox.com/assets/og/og-media-tools.svg"
  keywords="metronome, online metronome, bpm, beat keeper, music practice, tempo"
  h1="🎵 Metronome"
  subtitle="Online metronome for musicians. Adjustable tempo and time signatures."
  lastUpdated=""
  shareText="Free%20online%20Metronome%20on%20Webutilbox.%20Privacy-focused%2C%20runs%20100%25%20in%20your%20browser."
  shareUrl={canonical}
  embedUrl={canonical}
  embedTitle="Metronome - Online Beat Keeper for Musicians -- Webutilbox"
  embedHeight={600}
  toolCss={true}
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
>

<div class="workspace">
            <!-- Visual Beat Indicator -->
            <div style="text-align: center; padding: 40px; border: 2px solid var(--border); border-radius: 12px; background: var(--light); margin-bottom: 20px;">
                <div id="beatIndicator" style="width: 150px; height: 150px; margin: 0 auto 20px; border-radius: 50%; background: var(--dark); border: 4px solid var(--border); display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; font-size: 3rem; transition: all 0.1s;">
                    <span id="beatNumber">1</span>
                </div>

                <div id="bpmDisplay" style="font-size: 3rem; font-weight: bold; margin-bottom: 20px; color: var(--primary);">120</div>
                <div style="font-size: 1rem; color: var(--gray); margin-bottom: 30px;">BPM (Beats Per Minute)</div>

                <button id="startBtn" class="btn btn-primary" onclick="start()" style="padding: 15px 40px; font-size: 1.1rem;">
                    ▶️ Start
                </button>
                <button id="stopBtn" class="btn btn-danger" onclick="stop()" style="display: none; padding: 15px 40px; font-size: 1.1rem;">
                    🛑 Stop
                </button>
            </div>

            <!-- Controls -->
            <div style="background: var(--light); border-radius: 12px; padding: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px; border: 1px solid var(--border);">
                <!-- BPM Slider -->
                <div style="margin-bottom: 25px;">
                    <label style="font-size: 0.9rem; margin-bottom: 10px; display: block; font-weight: 600;">Tempo (BPM)</label>
                    <input type="range" id="bpmSlider" min="40" max="240" value="120" oninput="updateBPM()" style="width: 100%;">
                    <div style="display: flex; justify-content: space-between; margin-top: 8px; font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--gray);">
                        <span>40</span>
                        <span>240</span>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- BPM Input -->
                <div style="margin-bottom: 25px;">
                    <label style="font-size: 0.9rem; margin-bottom: 8px; display: block; font-weight: 600;">Enter BPM</label>
                    <input type="number" id="bpmInput" min="40" max="240" value="120" oninput="updateBPMFromInput()" style="width: 100%; padding: 12px; font-size: 1.1rem; text-align: center;">
                </div>

                <!-- Quick Tempos -->
                <div style="margin-bottom: 25px;">
                    <label style="font-size: 0.9rem; margin-bottom: 10px; display: block; font-weight: 600;">Quick Tempos</label>
                    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(120px, 1fr)); gap: 8px;">
                        <button class="btn" onclick="setBPM(60)" style="padding: 10px;">60 - Largo</button>
                        <button class="btn" onclick="setBPM(80)" style="padding: 10px;">80 - Andante</button>
                        <button class="btn" onclick="setBPM(100)" style="padding: 10px;">100 - Moderato</button>
                        <button class="btn" onclick="setBPM(120)" style="padding: 10px;">120 - Allegro</button>
                        <button class="btn" onclick="setBPM(140)" style="padding: 10px;">140 - Vivace</button>
                        <button class="btn" onclick="setBPM(180)" style="padding: 10px;">180 - Presto</button>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Time Signature -->
                <div style="margin-bottom: 25px;">
                    <label style="font-size: 0.9rem; margin-bottom: 8px; display: block; font-weight: 600;">Time Signature</label>
                    <select id="timeSignature" onchange="updateTimeSignature()" style="width: 100%; padding: 12px; font-size: 1rem;">
                        <option value="4">4/4 (Common Time)</option>
                        <option value="3">3/4 (Waltz)</option>
                        <option value="2">2/4 (March)</option>
                        <option value="6">6/8 (Compound)</option>
                        <option value="5">5/4 (Irregular)</option>
                        <option value="7">7/8 (Irregular)</option>
                    </select>
                </div>

                <!-- Volume -->
                <div>
                    <label style="font-size: 0.9rem; margin-bottom: 8px; display: block; font-weight: 600;">Volume</label>
                    <input type="range" id="volume" min="0" max="100" value="50" oninput="updateVolume()" style="width: 100%;">
                    <div style="text-align: center; margin-top: 5px; font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--gray);">
                        <span id="volumeValue">50</span>%
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Tap Tempo -->
            <div style="text-align: center; background: var(--light); border-radius: 12px; padding: 20px; border: 1px solid var(--border);">
                <button class="btn btn-primary" onclick="tapTempo()" style="padding: 20px 40px; font-size: 1.1rem;">
                    🥁 Tap Tempo
                </button>
                <p style="margin-top: 10px; font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--gray);">Tap this button repeatedly to set tempo</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        
        <!-- Share Bar -->

<style is:global>
.beat-active {
            background: var(--primary) !important;
            transform: scale(1.1);
            box-shadow: 0 0 30px rgba(249, 115, 22, 0.6);
        }
        .beat-accent {
            background: #10b981 !important;
        }
</style>


<script src="/js/metronome.js" defer></script>

<div class="info-section" slot="info">
<h2>Online Metronome - Free Beat Keeper for Musicians</h2>
            <p>Our free online metronome helps musicians of all levels practice with a steady, reliable beat. Set your tempo from 40 to 240 BPM, choose your time signature, and use the tap tempo feature to match any song — all without installing any software or app.</p>

            <h3>What Is a Metronome and Why Use One?</h3>
            <p>A metronome is a device or tool that produces a steady pulse at a set tempo, measured in beats per minute (BPM). Musicians use metronomes to develop a consistent internal sense of rhythm, which is one of the most fundamental skills in music performance.</p>
            <p>Practicing with a metronome trains your timing accuracy in a way that playing along to recordings cannot. A recording has a fixed tempo that you follow passively, but a metronome demands that you actively match its pulse, making you aware of every slight rush or drag in your playing. Over time, this builds the kind of rock-solid timing that separates amateur players from professionals.</p>
            <p>This online metronome uses the Web Audio API to generate precise, low-latency click sounds directly in your browser. The visual beat indicator flashes in sync with the audio, giving you both an auditory and visual reference for the beat.</p>

            <h3>Metronome Controls and Settings</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Adjustable tempo from 40 BPM (Largo) to 240 BPM (Prestissimo)</li>
                <li>Visual beat indicator with accent on beat 1 of each measure</li>
                <li>Tap tempo button — tap along to any song to detect its BPM automatically</li>
                <li>Six quick-select tempo presets: Largo, Andante, Moderato, Allegro, Vivace, Presto</li>
                <li>Multiple time signatures: 4/4, 3/4, 2/4, 6/8, 5/4, and 7/8</li>
                <li>Adjustable volume control</li>
                <li>Works entirely in the browser — no downloads or plugins required</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>How to Use the Online Metronome</h3>
            <p>Getting started with the metronome is simple. Here's how to set it up for your practice session:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Step 1: Set your desired tempo using the BPM slider or type a value directly into the BPM input field.</li>
                <li>Step 2: Select your time signature from the dropdown (4/4 for most pop and rock, 3/4 for waltz, etc.).</li>
                <li>Step 3: Adjust the volume to a comfortable level using the volume slider.</li>
                <li>Step 4: Click "Start" to begin the metronome. The visual indicator will flash on each beat, with a different color on beat 1.</li>
                <li>Step 5: Use the "Tap Tempo" button to detect the BPM of a song — just tap along to the beat several times.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Using a Metronome in Practice</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Practicing scales, arpeggios, and technical exercises on any instrument</li>
                <li>Learning a new piece of music by starting slow and gradually increasing tempo</li>
                <li>Rehearsing with a band to establish a consistent tempo before recording</li>
                <li>Identifying the BPM of a song using the tap tempo feature</li>
                <li>Practicing polyrhythms and odd time signatures like 5/4 or 7/8</li>
                <li>Drum practice and rhythm training for percussionists</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Getting the Most from a Metronome</h3>
            <p>One of the most effective ways to use a metronome is the "slow practice" method. Set the tempo significantly slower than your target speed — even 50–60% of the final tempo — and practice until you can play the passage perfectly at that speed. Then gradually increase the BPM in small increments (5–10 BPM at a time). This builds muscle memory correctly from the start, rather than reinforcing mistakes made at full speed.</p>
            <p>Don't always practice with the metronome clicking on every beat. Try setting it to click only on beats 1 and 3, or even just on beat 1. This forces you to internalize the subdivisions rather than relying on the click for every note. It's a more advanced technique that dramatically improves your internal clock.</p>
            <p>When using tap tempo, tap at least 4–8 times for an accurate reading. The tool averages your tap intervals, so more taps give a more precise BPM. Discard any taps older than 3 seconds automatically to keep the calculation fresh.</p>

            

            <h3>Audio Generated Client-Side Only</h3>
            <p>The metronome runs entirely in your browser using the Web Audio API.</p>
        
            <h3>Frequently Asked Questions</h3>
            <div class="faq-list">
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What BPM range does the metronome support?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>The metronome supports tempos from 20 BPM (very slow, largo) to 300 BPM (extremely fast). Common practice tempos range from 60-120 BPM. Most pop and rock songs are between 100-140 BPM.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What do the Italian tempo markings mean?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Common markings: Largo (40-60 BPM, very slow), Adagio (66-76 BPM, slow), Andante (76-108 BPM, walking pace), Moderato (108-120 BPM, moderate), Allegro (120-156 BPM, fast), Presto (168-200 BPM, very fast). These are guidelines, not strict rules.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can I set a time signature other than 4/4?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Yes. Common time signatures like 2/4, 3/4, 4/4, 6/8, and others are supported. The first beat of each measure is accented differently from the other beats so you can hear the downbeat clearly.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How do I use a metronome to improve my playing?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Start at a tempo where you can play perfectly with zero mistakes. Gradually increase by 2-5 BPM only when you can play flawlessly at the current tempo. Practicing with a metronome builds internal timing and reveals inconsistencies in your playing.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Does the metronome work without an internet connection?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Yes. Once the page is loaded, the metronome runs entirely in your browser using the Web Audio API. No internet connection is needed to use it.</p></div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="related-tools">
                <h3>Related Tools</h3>
                <div class="related-tools-grid">
                    <a href="../audio-visualizer/" class="related-tool-link">Audio Visualizer</a>
                    <a href="../audio-speed-changer/" class="related-tool-link">Audio Speed Changer</a>
                    <a href="../countdown-timer/" class="related-tool-link">Countdown Timer</a>
                    <a href="../stopwatch/" class="related-tool-link">Stopwatch</a>
                    <a href="../pomodoro-timer/" class="related-tool-link">Pomodoro Timer</a>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
</div>

</ToolLayout>